Overview¶

This assignment is open ended similar to the previous assignment. You will work with the SAME three data sets as in Homework 05. You already identified the BASIC and ESSENTIAL information for the variables (columns) in the three data sets. You calculated important summary statistics, and even examined if summary statistics changed based on different grouping variables. The Homework 05 exploration results were displayed within DataFrames and/or text. You printed results to the screen and provided Markdown text to accompany the table-like results.

You will repeat many of the same exploration steps from Homework 05, but this time you will visually explore the data! You will graphically display the exploratory results using plots/figures. You will explore marginal behavior by focusing on individual variables. Then you will explore combinations and relationships between 2 variables. The figures associated with studying relationships will graphically answer the SPLIT-APPLY-COMBINE related questions from the previous assignment. Certain tasks allow you to choose between Pandas plotting methods and Seaborn functions, while others state you must use Seaborn to create the figures.

The last question requires you to start visually exploring marginal behavior associated with one of the final projects of your choosing.

You must use the 3 data sets provided in Homework 05 Canvas assignment page. You may use the same data you previously downloaded, or redownload the CSV files to the appropriate directory on your computer.

Required tasks for Problem 01 through 03¶

For each of the 3 assigned data sets you must create plots/figures/charts to explore marginal behavior. You must therefore perform the following tasks:

  • Create BAR CHARTS to visually show the counts for the number of rows per unique value for NON-NUMERIC columns
    • You may use Pandas or Seaborn to create the bar charts
  • Create HISTOGRAMS to visually show the DISTRIBUTION of NUMERIC columns
    • You may use Pandas or Seaborn to create the histogram
  • IMPORTANT: You MUST visually explore the counts of NUMERIC columns that have less than 20 unique values as if they are NON-NUMERIC columns
  • IMPORTANT: After creating BAR CHARTS and HISTOGRAMS answer the following:
    • Do the categories of the NON-NUMERIC columns have similar counts?
    • Do the histograms of the NUMERIC columns look roughly like bell curves?

For each of the 3 assigned data sets you must create plots/figures/charts to explore combinations between 2 NON-NUMERIC columns. You must therefore perform the following tasks:

  • Create DODGED bar charts to visually show the COUNTS for COMBINATIONS between 2 NON-NUMERIC columns
    • You MUST create the DODGED bar chart using Seaborn
  • Create HEAT MAPS to visually show the COUNTS for COMBINATIONS between 2 NON-NUMERIC columns
    • You MUST create the HEAT MAP using Seaborn
    • The HEAT MAP MUST be annotated with count displayed as TEXT
  • IMPORTANT: You MUST treat NUMERIC columns that have less than 20 unique values as if they are NON-NUMERIC columns
  • IMPORTANT: After creating the DODGED bar charts and HEAT MAPS answer the following:
    • Are there combinations between the 2 variables NOT present in the data?
    • Which plot type was it easier to identify combinations that were NOT present?

For each of the 3 assigned data sets you must create plots/figures/charts to explore relationships between CATEGORICAL and CONTINUOUS variables. You must therefore explore the relationship between 1 NON-NUMERIC column and 1 NUMERIC column. You must perform the following tasks:

  • Create CONDITIONAL KDE plots to show the conditional distribution of the NUMERIC column CONDITIONED ON (or GROUPED BY) the NON-NUMERIC column
    • You MUST create the CONDITIONAL KDE plot using Seaborn with the NON-NUMERIC column associated with the KDE COLOR
    • You MUST remove the SAMPLE SIZE issue with the CONDITIONAL KDE plot
  • Create BOXPLOTS to show if the SUMMARY STATISTICS of the NUMERIC column CHANGE across the CATEGORIES of the NON-NUMERIC column
    • You MUST create the BOXPLOT using Seaborn
  • Create POINT PLOTS to show if the CONDITIONAL MEAN of the NUMERIC columns CHANGE across the CATEGORIES of the NON-NUMERIC column
    • You MUST create the POINT PLOT using Seaborn
  • IMPORTANT: You MUST treat NUMERIC columns that have less than 20 unique values as if they are NON-NUMERIC columns
  • IMPORTANT: After creating the figures you must answer the following:
    • Does the distributional SHAPE of a NUMERIC column appear to be different across the CATEGORIES of the NON-NUMERIC column?
    • Does the MEDIAN of the NUMERIC column appear to be different across the CATEGORIES of the NON-NUMERIC column?
    • Does the VARIATION of the NUMERIC column appear to be different across the CATEGORIES of the NON-NUMERIC column?
    • Are you confident that the MEAN of the NUMERIC column CHANGES across the CATEGORIES of the NON-NUMERIC column?

HEAT MAP is easier to identify combinations that were NOT present.
